<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-07-22T00:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-07-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="388" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d388">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/7–2244: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-07-22T12:00:00+07:00">July 22,
                                1944—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received July 22—9:53 a.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>1273. Rice reports from Sian [that] Yenan press party has divided, Father
                        Shanahan and Chinese newspapermen being en route from Sian to Chungking,
                        other foreign correspondents visiting Northwest Shansi to return via
                        Ninghsia.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>